Data Description¶

https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/quality-and-outcomes-framework-achievement-prevalence-and-exceptions-data/2019-20 https://qof.digital.nhs.uk/

Table 3: Prevalence, achievement and personalised care adjustments, cardiovascular group, cardiovascular disease – primary prevention, 2019-20, GP practice level

Definitions¶

Following definitions have been taken from the resource links above.

  • Prevalence: A measure of the frequency of a disease of health condition
  • Achievement: The QOF gives an indication of the overall achievement of a practice through a points system. Reference to 100 per cent achievement often refers to the percentage of available QOF points achieved.
  • Exceptions: Exception reporting’ refers to the potential removal of these patients from calculations of practice achievement for specific clinical indicators.
  • Personalised Care Adjustment (PCA): As of 1 April 2019, exception reporting was replaced with Personalised Care Adjustments (PCAs). Unlike exception reporting, PCAs are extracted in the same order for all indicators, enabling more robust insight to be gained from their analysis.
  • CVDPP001: In those patients with a new diagnosis of hypertension aged 30 or over and who have not attained the age of 75, recorded between the preceding 1 April to 31 March (excluding those with pre-existing CHD, diabetes, stroke and/or TIA), who have a recorded CVD risk assessment score (using an assessment tool agreed with the NHS CB) of ≥20% in the preceding 12 months: the percentage who are currently treated with statins.

Reading data to Pandas DataFrame¶

A pandas dataframe will be our preferred data structure, and to convert from our existing Excel Worksheet structure I require some wrangling/formatting.

  1. Parsing of header
  2. Selecting slice of worksheet which contains corresponding data
In [3]:
wb = load_workbook('data/qof-1920-prev-ach-pca-cv-prac.xlsx')
ws = wb['CVD-PP']
In [4]:
'''
Parsing of the header.
Header spans three rows of the worksheet
Header contains merged rows on row 12
'''
ws['A12'] = None # remove 'Return to Contents' link from header row
header_cols = []
init_col = ''
for cells in zip(ws[12], ws[13], ws[14]):
    if cells[0].value:
        init_col = col = str(cells[0].value)
    elif type(cells[0]) is openpyxl.cell.cell.MergedCell:
        col = init_col
    else:
        col = ''
    for cell in [cells[1], cells[2]]:
        val = cell.value
        if val:
            col += str(val)
    header_cols.append(col)

In [11]:
def summarise_col(col):
    '''
    Returns a summary stats for a pandas series
    '''
    nunique = col.nunique()
    if col.dtype != 'O':
        mean = col.mean()
        std = col.std()
        min_ = col.min()
        max_ = col.max()
        return nunique, mean, std, min_, max_
    else:
        return nunique, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan

The data is now cleaned for use within an EDA. We notice:

  • Each line is for each Practice and Practices can be grouped into Primary Care Networks (PCNs) and Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs).
  • We have separate columns for 2018-2019 and 2019-2020.
  • Exceptions in 2018-2019 get changed to PCAs in 2019-2020.
  • 'Total Achievement Score (max 10 per practice)' and 'Achievement (%)' are equivalent and one of columns can be dropped for further analysis.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

First we look at some correlations, mainly we can look at Prevalence, Achievement and Exclusions/PCA across 2018-19, 2019-20 and CVDPP001.

In [16]:
def corr_plot(df):
    '''
    Creates a heatmap for a correlation matrix for a visual representation
    of correlation matrix.
    '''
    corr = df.corr()
    mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette(200, 0, as_cmap=True)
    plot = sns.heatmap(corr,
                      mask=mask,
                      cmap=cmap,
                      vmax=1,
                      center=0,
                      square=True,
                      linewidths=1)
    annot_plot = sns.heatmap(corr[(corr >= 0.5) | (corr <= -0.5)],
                      mask=mask,
                      cmap=cmap,
                      vmax=1,
                      center=0,
                      square=True,
                      linewidths=1,
                      annot=True,
                      cbar=False)
    return corr, plot, annot_plot
In [17]:
_, plot, annot_plot = corr_plot(df.iloc[:, 3:])
plot;
annot_plot;

We can notice:

  • High Positive correlation with CVDPP001 Achievement and Underlying Achievement net of PCAs with 2019-20 Achievement. Similarly with Denominators.
    • NOTE: CVDPP001PCA Rate and 2019-2020Overall PCA Rate, CVDPP001PCAs and 2019-20Total PCAs, CVDPP001Denominator and 2019-20Total Denominations, CVDPP001Achievement Score and 2019-20Achievement variable pairings have all correlation of 1 and thus we can omit redundent columns.
  • Negative correlation with CVDPP001 Patients receiving Intervention and PCA Rates and Total PCAs, but not as much with Exceptions.
  • General Positive correlations with many variables which may indicate multicollinearity we might be vary of if used in predictive models.
  • We may expect that Overall Exception Rate and Total Exceptions would have a higher correlation.

Dimensionality Reduction (Principal Component Analysis)¶

As seen above dimensionality reduction may be able to explain our data with reducing complexity.

We that the first 9 principal components are able to explain 94% of the variance in our dataset, allowing for a reduction of 11 features. Benefits from dimensionality reduction include:

  • Reducing affects of curse of dimensionality
  • Reducing size and processing load
  • Removal of some multicollinearity, improving interpretation of features for ML purposes.

Conclusions¶

Our data is sourced from NHS digital Quality of Outcomes Framework (QOF), and is a worksheet containing the prevalence, achievement and PCAs for cardiovascular disease. Each line contains the results for a practice and each practice belongs to groups CCGs and PCNs.

For use in analysis we first required some work for parsing correctly the data, selecting data rows and parsing header, as data is in Excel worksheet format. We also note ':' and 'z' being used for missing or not available data.

We see correlations with all '2018-19', '2019-20' and 'CVDPP001' of respective columns and thus dived a bit further with exploring clustering and dimensionality reduction. We notice when varying 'PCN ODS code' cluster predictions change. With '2018-19Register' we notice a pattern within principal components. Also we clearly can benefit from dimension reduction as PCA can explain 94% of the data's variance with while reducing from 20 to 9 features. If more time available encoding the 'CCG ODS code' and 'PCN ODS code' together with the clustering and dimension reduction analysis may give us further insight, and discover more patterns.
